1
00:00:51,969 --> 00:00:55,322
- It's lucky it didn't reach the house.
- Yeah.

2
00:00:56,783 --> 00:00:58,333
You know,

3
00:00:58,340 --> 00:01:02,186
there's gonna be a lot more jobs at
that factory in Milwaukee come June.

4
00:01:04,126 --> 00:01:07,867
- I could put in a word.
- You can't leave us, Henry.

5
00:01:07,890 --> 00:01:09,922
She needs us both.

6
00:01:09,945 --> 00:01:12,818
Can you stop being a momma's boy
for one second?

7
00:01:14,467 --> 00:01:16,768
I'm not trying to hurt you, but Jesus,

8
00:01:16,792 --> 00:01:19,010
you got to live your own life sometime.

9
00:01:19,034 --> 00:01:21,614
That woman can take care
of her own goddamn...

10
00:01:34,981 --> 00:01:36,907
Oh, good evening.

11
00:01:36,930 --> 00:01:40,018
Brother has been killing brother
since Cain and Abel,

12
00:01:40,042 --> 00:01:42,417
yet even I didn't see that coming.

13
00:01:42,440 --> 00:01:46,022
I was as blind-sided as poor
old Henry down there.

14
00:01:46,045 --> 00:01:50,638
Apparently the authorities
shared my naivet?

15
00:01:50,661 --> 00:01:54,021
In other words,
they believed the young man's story

16
00:01:54,044 --> 00:01:57,085
that Henry fell,
hit his head on a stone,

17
00:01:57,106 --> 00:02:00,438
and died of smoke asphyxiation.

18
00:02:01,976 --> 00:02:04,994
On the other hand,
if they hadn't believed him,

19
00:02:05,017 --> 00:02:09,473
Ed Gein would never have had
the opportunity to commit those

20
00:02:09,493 --> 00:02:14,371
heinous crimes
for which he became most famous.

21
00:02:14,395 --> 00:02:20,033
And we, of course, well... We wouldn't
have our little movie, would we?

22
00:02:20,819 --> 00:02:25,797
Sync, corrected by icephoenix

23
00:02:38,731 --> 00:02:40,343
Here he comes!

24
00:02:44,389 --> 00:02:46,575
This thing's going to be gigantic.

25
00:02:46,598 --> 00:02:49,264
I wish I had 20% of the take.

26
00:02:49,289 --> 00:02:52,244
Does tonight's incredible reaction
surprise you, Mr. Hitchcock?

27
00:02:52,267 --> 00:02:55,148
No, when I was planning
North by Northwest

28
00:02:55,163 --> 00:02:58,950
I could already hear the
screams and the laughter.

29
00:02:59,498 --> 00:03:03,198
Any questions, my dear?
Pity.

30
00:03:03,209 --> 00:03:06,914
Mr. Hitchcock,
you've directed 46 motion pictures.

31
00:03:06,937 --> 00:03:09,321
You're the most famous director
in the history of the medium...

32
00:03:09,339 --> 00:03:11,810
But you're sixty years old.

33
00:03:11,834 --> 00:03:14,023
Shouldn't you just quit
while you're ahead?

34
00:03:30,271 --> 00:03:34,748
Muhammad had the eyes of peeping Toms
gouged out with arrows.

35
00:03:34,768 --> 00:03:37,791
That must have been rather painful.

36
00:03:37,803 --> 00:03:39,858
Talking of arrows,

37
00:03:39,881 --> 00:03:44,963
did you read that little snippet from A.H.
Weiler's review in The New York Times?

38
00:03:44,987 --> 00:03:48,822
He said he found the climax
to be "overdrawn."

39
00:03:48,845 --> 00:03:52,535
Yes, well I doubt Mr. Weiler has
had a climax in years.

40
00:03:52,558 --> 00:03:56,820
"North by Northwest
reminds us of Mr. Hitchcock's

41
00:03:56,843 --> 00:04:00,474
earlier, more inventive spy thrillers."

42
00:04:00,497 --> 00:04:03,010
And there is an accompanying list.

43
00:04:03,033 --> 00:04:07,166
The "New Masters of Suspense."

44
00:04:07,190 --> 00:04:10,851
Why do they keep looking for new ones
when they still have the original?

45
00:04:10,874 --> 00:04:13,666
Oh, don't be maudlin,
you know how much it aggravates me.

46
00:04:13,690 --> 00:04:15,559
Just stop reading them.

47
00:04:15,582 --> 00:04:17,440
You've been reading them for a week.

48
00:04:18,566 --> 00:04:20,045
Tell me, my dear,

49
00:04:20,069 --> 00:04:22,466
do you think I'm too old?

50
00:04:24,285 --> 00:04:27,252
Yes, you're a true relic.

51
00:04:27,275 --> 00:04:30,425
And lest we forget,
a notably corpulent one.

52
00:04:31,468 --> 00:04:35,843
You always know precisely
where to plunge the dagger, don't you?

53
00:04:35,866 --> 00:04:38,948
Right between the shoulder blades.
I learned it from your pictures.

54
00:04:38,972 --> 00:04:41,755
Where, may I ask, are you off to?

55
00:04:41,778 --> 00:04:43,704
I'm going to have brunch with Whit

56
00:04:43,727 --> 00:04:46,353
after I drop you off at the studio.
Would you care to join us?

57
00:04:46,376 --> 00:04:49,162
We've just established that
I'm far too corpulent

58
00:04:49,163 --> 00:04:51,275
to be seen in broad daylight.

59
00:04:51,299 --> 00:04:54,064
Oh, you'll feel better when
you find a new project.

60
00:04:54,087 --> 00:04:56,730
Hasn't Peggy unearthed any
decent books for you recently?

61
00:04:56,753 --> 00:04:59,788
Yes, sleeping pills with dust jackets.

62
00:05:00,982 --> 00:05:03,911
So what do you think?

63
00:05:04,849 --> 00:05:07,198
Very presentable.

64
00:05:10,374 --> 00:05:12,781
Hurry up, dear, you're pruning.

65
00:05:23,839 --> 00:05:26,082
- Good Morning.
- Ms. Hitchcock.

66
00:05:26,105 --> 00:05:27,796
Mr. Hitchcock.

67
00:05:27,819 --> 00:05:29,424
Sirs.

68
00:05:37,384 --> 00:05:41,117
There's a project out there waiting
for you, Hitch. I promise you.

69
00:05:41,141 --> 00:05:44,474
- I hope so. Thank you, love.
- Have a good day.

70
00:05:47,934 --> 00:05:52,290
I'm treading water, Peggy. I need
something fresh, something different.

71
00:05:52,314 --> 00:05:55,403
Without expensive stars to pretty it up.

72
00:05:55,427 --> 00:05:59,544
Fox is offering you The Diary of
Anne Frank for the third time.

73
00:05:59,567 --> 00:06:02,458
The audience would spend the entire
picture waiting for Miss Frank

74
00:06:02,459 --> 00:06:05,280
to discover the corpse
I'd hidden in the attic.

75
00:06:05,301 --> 00:06:07,614
- Wouldn't you agree, Nuncio?
- Si.

76
00:06:07,638 --> 00:06:10,945
MGM wants you for the Ian Fleming book,
Casino Royale.

77
00:06:10,969 --> 00:06:13,540
Cary Grant.
Definitely your style.

78
00:06:13,564 --> 00:06:17,431
Doesn't she know I just made that movie?
It's called North by Northwest.

79
00:06:17,449 --> 00:06:20,279
"Style," my dear, is mere self-plagiarism.

80
00:06:20,302 --> 00:06:22,826
Oh, scusi!

81
00:06:22,850 --> 00:06:26,736
A nice, clean, nasty little piece of work.
That's what I'm looking for.

82
00:06:26,760 --> 00:06:29,118
I shall see what I can find.

83
00:06:31,929 --> 00:06:33,816
- Serves you right.
- Yeah.

84
00:06:34,614 --> 00:06:37,665
You know, Hitch always says that
your private life

85
00:06:37,666 --> 00:06:40,623
is in danger of being more entertaining
than any of your plots.

86
00:06:40,647 --> 00:06:44,034
I'm surprised he let me have you
for the whole afternoon.

87
00:06:44,057 --> 00:06:46,287
Especially looking so beautiful.

88
00:06:46,309 --> 00:06:49,880
So tell me,
what are you working on these days?

89
00:06:49,903 --> 00:06:52,289
Me? Oh, oh...

90
00:06:52,313 --> 00:06:54,685
I'm satisfied working in my garden.

91
00:06:54,708 --> 00:06:57,800
Oh!
Well that's one lucky garden.

92
00:06:59,185 --> 00:07:04,140
All this relentless sycophancy is
actually giving me indigestion.

93
00:07:04,164 --> 00:07:06,806
What are you after?

94
00:07:06,829 --> 00:07:13,627
I was hoping you may be able to apply
your considerable pruning skills to this.

95
00:07:13,650 --> 00:07:18,918
Ah, all is finally revealed.

96
00:07:18,941 --> 00:07:22,181
Whit, you are a little predictable.

97
00:07:24,067 --> 00:07:27,042
The most fun I ever had
was working with you.

98
00:07:43,956 --> 00:07:46,879
Anything come up, my dear?
Anything at all?

99
00:07:46,903 --> 00:07:48,828
Nothing suitable.

100
00:07:48,852 --> 00:07:51,111
Is that water
or do I need to call Alma?

101
00:07:51,130 --> 00:07:52,967
Do whatever you want.

102
00:07:55,671 --> 00:08:00,532
Anthony Boucher says that
this book Psycho by Robert Bloch is

103
00:08:00,555 --> 00:08:03,281
"fiendishly entertaining."

104
00:08:03,303 --> 00:08:05,715
It sounds ghastly.
Everyone in town's already passed.

105
00:08:05,739 --> 00:08:07,699
And who is everyone, pray?

106
00:08:07,711 --> 00:08:11,468
The story department finished the
coverage this morning.

107
00:08:12,826 --> 00:08:16,839
This about Ed Gein,
the mass murderer from Wisconsin?

108
00:08:16,853 --> 00:08:18,591
Oh, yeah.

109
00:08:18,614 --> 00:08:24,849
"Graphic elements of brutal violence,
voyeurism, transvestitism and incest."

110
00:08:24,866 --> 00:08:30,146
Very nice. Not your average
run-of-the-mill nutcase, is he?

111
00:08:30,170 --> 00:08:32,334
You're kidding.

112
00:08:32,357 --> 00:08:35,805
Peggy, this is the boy
who dug up his own mother.

113
00:08:48,713 --> 00:08:50,862
- Hungry?
- Famished.

114
00:08:50,885 --> 00:08:54,019
You can have half a grapefruit later
if you're good.

115
00:08:54,042 --> 00:08:55,956
Listen, Hitch.

116
00:08:55,980 --> 00:08:59,223
Whit gave me the galleys to his new book
yesterday at lunch.

117
00:08:59,247 --> 00:09:02,123
I've already got some ideas
about how we can adapt it.

118
00:09:02,147 --> 00:09:05,329
It's elegant. It's sophisticated.
It's full of intrigue.

119
00:09:05,352 --> 00:09:08,454
You mean the book or Mr. Whitfield Cook?

120
00:09:10,626 --> 00:09:12,771
This could be the one, Hitch.

121
00:09:14,468 --> 00:09:16,535
I'll read it later.

122
00:09:18,663 --> 00:09:21,323
There are calories in that, you know.

123
00:09:36,666 --> 00:09:37,887
Ma?

124
00:09:40,215 --> 00:09:41,401
Ma...

125
00:09:44,317 --> 00:09:46,869
Aren't you cold?

126
00:10:11,401 --> 00:10:14,243
No need to be afraid, Ma.

127
00:10:23,845 --> 00:10:26,123
Oh, God!

128
00:10:26,146 --> 00:10:30,912
I just want you to read
this little bit here.

129
00:10:30,936 --> 00:10:34,951
It takes place in the motel bathroom.

130
00:10:34,963 --> 00:10:37,206
"Mary started to scream,

131
00:10:37,229 --> 00:10:39,562
"and then the curtains parted further

132
00:10:39,576 --> 00:10:43,147
"and a hand appeared,
holding a butcher's knife.

133
00:10:43,171 --> 00:10:45,824
"It was the knife that, a moment later,

134
00:10:45,836 --> 00:10:49,222
cut off her scream,
and her head."

135
00:10:50,500 --> 00:10:54,213
Charming.
Doris Day should do it as a musical.

136
00:10:54,237 --> 00:10:59,142
That is nothing but low-budget
horror movie claptrap.

137
00:11:01,582 --> 00:11:06,276
But what if someone really good
made a horror picture?

138
00:11:08,559 --> 00:11:11,672
Just think of the shock value.

139
00:11:11,696 --> 00:11:15,121
Killing off your leading lady
halfway through.

140
00:11:17,237 --> 00:11:20,288
I mean, you are intrigued,
are you not, my dear?

141
00:11:21,545 --> 00:11:23,751
Come on, admit it.

142
00:11:23,774 --> 00:11:26,064
Admit it.

143
00:11:26,087 --> 00:11:28,847
Actually, I think it's a huge mistake.

144
00:11:32,657 --> 00:11:36,146
You shouldn't wait till halfway through.
Kill her off after thirty minutes.

145
00:11:38,745 --> 00:11:40,882
Well!

146
00:11:41,552 --> 00:11:45,360
Peggy,
I want you to summon your minions.

147
00:11:45,384 --> 00:11:48,131
- Minions?
- Right away.

148
00:11:48,154 --> 00:11:51,343
Certainly.
And who might they be?

149
00:11:51,366 --> 00:11:55,100
Get them started buying copies of Psycho.

150
00:11:55,124 --> 00:11:58,618
- How many do you need?
- All of them. Every copy, nationwide.

151
00:11:58,642 --> 00:12:01,906
Scour every bookshop, every library.
And I mean everywhere.

152
00:12:01,929 --> 00:12:03,879
Psycho is going to be my next movie,

153
00:12:03,903 --> 00:12:07,417
and I don't want anyone to know the ending
until they see it in the theater.

154
00:12:09,659 --> 00:12:12,210
Look at that.

155
00:12:14,738 --> 00:12:19,976
Are you sure about this?
This is so unlike you.

156
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:23,048
That is exactly the point, my dear.

157
00:12:26,732 --> 00:12:30,119
Ladies and gentlemen of the press,

158
00:12:33,311 --> 00:12:35,350
good afternoon.

159
00:12:36,399 --> 00:12:41,041
I see you've all been devouring
the article on Mr. Ed Gein.

160
00:12:41,052 --> 00:12:42,670
Violent chap,

161
00:12:42,694 --> 00:12:47,457
and the real-life inspiration
behind Psycho.

162
00:12:47,477 --> 00:12:52,686
All of us harbor
dark recesses of violence,

163
00:12:52,709 --> 00:12:55,633
and horror.

164
00:12:55,656 --> 00:12:58,573
Fascinating, isn't it?

165
00:12:58,597 --> 00:13:04,045
When the Wisconsin Police Department
raided Mr. Gein's farm,

166
00:13:04,068 --> 00:13:08,464
they opened the door...
And voila!

167
00:13:08,489 --> 00:13:14,137
They discovered ten female heads
with the tops sawn off.

168
00:13:14,160 --> 00:13:16,987
Pass these around, would you?
And have a look.

169
00:13:17,010 --> 00:13:19,476
Masks of human skin.

170
00:13:19,500 --> 00:13:23,284
A pair of lips on a drawstring
for a window shade.

171
00:13:23,308 --> 00:13:26,037
Oh, yes, and a jug
containing human noses.

172
00:13:26,060 --> 00:13:29,606
Is this really going to be your
next picture, Mr. Hitchcock?

173
00:13:29,630 --> 00:13:32,138
Well, that is my intention, yes, madam.

174
00:13:32,161 --> 00:13:35,003
My only wish is that Ed
Gein looked a little

175
00:13:35,004 --> 00:13:37,844
more like William Holden
instead of Elmer Fudd.

176
00:13:40,975 --> 00:13:45,074
By the way, try the finger sandwiches.
They're real fingers.

177
00:13:46,313 --> 00:13:49,522
Bloody hell!

178
00:13:49,546 --> 00:13:51,647
Now don't pretend you're
not upset he hasn't read it.

179
00:13:51,670 --> 00:13:53,744
I'm not.
I'm a big boy, I can take it.

180
00:13:53,767 --> 00:13:55,529
Well, I loved it.

181
00:13:55,552 --> 00:13:58,657
It must be great fun to research.

182
00:13:58,681 --> 00:14:01,339
Do you really think he will read it?

183
00:14:01,351 --> 00:14:04,075
Ah, speak of the devil.

184
00:14:04,087 --> 00:14:08,161
Hitch, I ran all over town
trying to find a copy of Psycho

185
00:14:08,185 --> 00:14:10,415
but I simply cannot find one.

186
00:14:10,439 --> 00:14:15,029
- I wonder how that could have happened.
- Yeah.

187
00:14:15,041 --> 00:14:17,818
Don't stop looking on my behalf.

188
00:14:17,842 --> 00:14:20,354
Hitch, you should come.

189
00:14:26,392 --> 00:14:30,033
I've seen happier faces on a school bus
going over a cliff.

190
00:14:32,674 --> 00:14:36,453
But they can't stop looking, can they?

191
00:14:42,348 --> 00:14:45,047
Audiences want to be shocked, Barney.

192
00:14:45,071 --> 00:14:47,642
They want something different.

193
00:14:47,654 --> 00:14:49,286
And this is it.

194
00:14:49,310 --> 00:14:52,726
Every time you want to do
something different

195
00:14:52,749 --> 00:14:57,185
like The Wrong Man or Vertigo,
someone loses money.

196
00:14:57,210 --> 00:15:00,498
So we should stop trying to
give them something new?

197
00:15:00,522 --> 00:15:03,718
You owe Paramount one last picture,
Hitch.

198
00:15:03,742 --> 00:15:06,771
Can't you do something like
North by Northwest

199
00:15:06,795 --> 00:15:10,163
but for us this time
instead of for MGM?

200
00:15:12,751 --> 00:15:14,956
Psycho.

201
00:15:18,132 --> 00:15:21,673
No one respects
the name Hitchcock like Paramount.

202
00:15:23,991 --> 00:15:27,894
Are you telling me "no," Barney?

203
00:15:27,917 --> 00:15:30,923
I think you know me better than that,
Hitch.

204
00:15:33,306 --> 00:15:34,879
What a putz.

205
00:15:34,891 --> 00:15:38,251
You know what his family did
before they built those movie palaces?

206
00:15:38,274 --> 00:15:40,440
Ran a grocery store.

207
00:15:40,464 --> 00:15:44,491
My father ran a grocery store.

208
00:15:44,515 --> 00:15:48,252
Exactly. That's what I'm saying.
He should show some respect.

209
00:15:49,814 --> 00:15:53,731
They think I've lost my touch, Lew.

210
00:15:53,755 --> 00:15:57,923
My association with television has
cheapened me.

211
00:15:57,946 --> 00:16:00,071
Are you referring to that deal I got you

212
00:16:00,095 --> 00:16:03,873
where Bristol-Meyers pays you 29 grand
an episode and you own the negative?

213
00:16:03,896 --> 00:16:06,296
That's my kind of cheap.

214
00:16:06,318 --> 00:16:10,151
They just want the same thing
over and over and over.

215
00:16:10,175 --> 00:16:13,880
They've put me in a coffin and
now they're nailing down the lid.

216
00:16:13,903 --> 00:16:18,065
Hitch, as your agent,
I will never let that happen.

217
00:16:22,307 --> 00:16:25,989
How much you think you can
make this picture for?

218
00:16:26,012 --> 00:16:28,770
$800,000, give or take.

219
00:16:37,544 --> 00:16:39,920
You're home early.

220
00:16:42,769 --> 00:16:45,192
Oh, it's lovely actually.

221
00:16:56,070 --> 00:17:01,330
You know, I'm disappointed
you didn't give Whit's book a chance.

222
00:17:01,353 --> 00:17:03,498
And what about Whit?
Is he disappointed?

223
00:17:03,522 --> 00:17:05,846
Oh, no.
He knows you well enough.

224
00:17:05,869 --> 00:17:09,814
Look at that!
Time for a new one anyway.

225
00:17:09,838 --> 00:17:13,233
Well you'd better enjoy the pool,
my dear, while you can.

226
00:17:15,835 --> 00:17:19,311
We might not have it much longer.

227
00:17:19,335 --> 00:17:20,732
Why?

228
00:17:20,755 --> 00:17:23,889
Paramount refuses to finance the movie.

229
00:17:23,913 --> 00:17:27,487
Oh, Hitch, I'm so sorry.

230
00:17:27,511 --> 00:17:32,024
Lew can't find the money.
At least, not fast enough.

231
00:17:32,041 --> 00:17:33,558
Well why not wait?

232
00:17:35,429 --> 00:17:37,070
No.

233
00:17:39,712 --> 00:17:44,811
Just going to have to go it alone,
old girl.

234
00:17:44,835 --> 00:17:47,209
Finance it ourselves.

235
00:17:54,274 --> 00:17:58,019
Are we going to have to sell
the whole house or just the pool?

236
00:17:59,563 --> 00:18:02,571
I just want to do the film.

237
00:18:08,800 --> 00:18:12,223
I will ask you this once
and I'll never mention it again.

238
00:18:13,503 --> 00:18:15,857
Why this one, Hitch?

239
00:18:17,759 --> 00:18:21,573
It's not just because so many people
are saying "no," is it?

240
00:18:23,137 --> 00:18:27,165
Do you remember the fun we had
when we started out all those years ago?

241
00:18:28,685 --> 00:18:31,249
We didn't have any money then, did we?

242
00:18:31,270 --> 00:18:34,753
We didn't have any time, either,
but we took risks, do you remember?

243
00:18:36,674 --> 00:18:43,920
We experimented.
We invented new ways of making pictures

244
00:18:43,944 --> 00:18:46,430
because we had to.

245
00:18:49,013 --> 00:18:55,206
I want to feel
that kind of freedom again.

246
00:18:58,060 --> 00:19:00,414
Like we used to, you know?

247
00:19:06,683 --> 00:19:12,694
We are about to propose
a restructured deal for Psycho.

248
00:19:12,718 --> 00:19:15,031
I'm listening.

249
00:19:15,043 --> 00:19:19,312
We finance it independently.

250
00:19:19,335 --> 00:19:24,518
Hitch waives his directorial fee.
Paramount only distributes it,

251
00:19:24,542 --> 00:19:28,203
in exchange for 40% of the profits.

252
00:19:28,226 --> 00:19:33,440
Interesting. But what exactly
is Paramount distributing?

253
00:19:33,463 --> 00:19:37,790
Is this still a picture about a queer
killing people in his mother's dress?

254
00:19:37,813 --> 00:19:41,690
What this picture is about
is the reputation of Alfred Hitchcock.

255
00:19:41,713 --> 00:19:45,283
- No one is arguing that.
- Barney,

256
00:19:45,306 --> 00:19:48,488
it's very simple.

257
00:19:48,512 --> 00:19:51,545
This is Mr. Hitchcock's next film.

258
00:19:51,566 --> 00:19:56,142
Are you in or are you out?

259
00:20:01,328 --> 00:20:05,312
Fine. We'll take that deal.

260
00:20:07,199 --> 00:20:09,895
If you can get the money.

261
00:20:09,919 --> 00:20:13,018
We already have the money, Barney.

262
00:20:19,607 --> 00:20:22,991
Who do I make it out to?

263
00:20:28,034 --> 00:20:31,357
If this picture fails, Alma,

264
00:20:31,381 --> 00:20:36,500
we'll be in for a long,
humiliating bout of crow-eating.

265
00:20:38,741 --> 00:20:43,720
- It'll be splendid.
- Are you sure?

266
00:20:43,743 --> 00:20:48,871
Of the movie? Not at all.

267
00:20:48,895 --> 00:20:53,291
But of you? Unquestionably.

268
00:20:59,679 --> 00:21:01,100
Ahem.

269
00:21:02,990 --> 00:21:05,738
- Joe Stefano. Good to meet you.
- Sit down.

270
00:21:05,761 --> 00:21:07,323
I'm sorry I was late.

271
00:21:07,346 --> 00:21:09,542
My shrink session went overtime.

272
00:21:12,624 --> 00:21:15,701
I see him every day
and it's still not enough.

273
00:21:15,725 --> 00:21:19,511
I thought it was only director's
assistants who needed psychiatrists,

274
00:21:19,523 --> 00:21:21,730
not writers.

275
00:21:26,143 --> 00:21:28,467
Do you see a shrink, Mr. Hitchcock?

276
00:21:28,491 --> 00:21:31,228
I have to confess, Mr. Stefano,

277
00:21:31,252 --> 00:21:33,846
It boggles my brain
just trying to imagine

278
00:21:33,869 --> 00:21:36,863
what you and your shrink
could possibly talk about every day.

279
00:21:40,007 --> 00:21:44,206
The usual: Sex. Rage. My mother.

280
00:21:54,124 --> 00:21:56,466
Good morning, sir.

281
00:21:58,929 --> 00:22:00,091
Let me have a look at you.

282
00:22:00,115 --> 00:22:04,920
The only thing worse than a visit to
the dentist is a visit to censor.

283
00:22:04,943 --> 00:22:07,855
Whatever you do, Hitch,
don't lose your temper.

284
00:22:09,677 --> 00:22:11,382
- See you later.
- Good luck.

285
00:22:14,358 --> 00:22:17,975
The Code will absolutely not permit you

286
00:22:17,998 --> 00:22:21,227
to show a knife
penetrating a woman's flesh.

287
00:22:21,251 --> 00:22:23,056
I assure you, Geoffrey,

288
00:22:23,080 --> 00:22:28,317
my murders are always models of taste
and discretion.

289
00:22:28,341 --> 00:22:31,954
Is there any improper
suggestion of nudity in this

290
00:22:31,978 --> 00:22:34,223
murder scene in the shower?

291
00:22:34,247 --> 00:22:38,335
She won't be nude.
She'll be wearing a shower cap.

292
00:22:43,395 --> 00:22:46,659
We might accept a shot
from outside the bathroom window

293
00:22:46,683 --> 00:22:49,042
of Marion in silhouette
above the shoulders.

294
00:22:49,066 --> 00:22:51,848
Provided that the glass is frosted.

295
00:22:52,602 --> 00:22:54,281
Thank you.

296
00:22:54,304 --> 00:22:58,647
And the scene with the toilet.

297
00:22:58,670 --> 00:23:01,118
It is completely necessary
to show the toilet,

298
00:23:01,141 --> 00:23:04,602
because Marion Crane attempts
to flush evidence down it.

299
00:23:04,621 --> 00:23:07,615
Remnants of which are later
discovered by her sister.

300
00:23:07,639 --> 00:23:13,641
These remnants, you understand,
are clues to her vanishing.

301
00:23:13,664 --> 00:23:18,505
No American movie has ever found it
necessary to show a toilet,

302
00:23:18,528 --> 00:23:20,818
let alone to flush one.

303
00:23:20,842 --> 00:23:23,935
Perhaps we ought to
shoot the film in France

304
00:23:23,936 --> 00:23:26,540
and use a bidet instead.

305
00:23:29,712 --> 00:23:35,003
Mr. Hitchcock,
if this office denies you a seal,

306
00:23:35,027 --> 00:23:37,569
and we're certainly heading
in that direction,

307
00:23:37,592 --> 00:23:43,159
your movie will not be released
in a single theater in this country.

308
00:23:43,183 --> 00:23:46,086
Will you be making jokes then?

309
00:23:48,063 --> 00:23:51,877
Everyone in Hollywood resents me.

310
00:23:51,901 --> 00:23:54,255
I make them millions of dollars,

311
00:23:54,279 --> 00:23:59,058
and every year I sit at those
dreadful award show dinners,

312
00:23:59,081 --> 00:24:03,205
waiting for someone just to say,
"You're good."

313
00:24:05,335 --> 00:24:10,835
They take sadistic pleasure in
denying me that one little moment.

314
00:24:10,858 --> 00:24:12,981
That must hurt.

315
00:24:15,390 --> 00:24:19,954
Deeply, Ed. Deeply.

316
00:24:20,873 --> 00:24:26,521
Sorry, doctor.
I'm just not used to this...

317
00:24:27,360 --> 00:24:29,434
process.

318
00:24:30,569 --> 00:24:34,158
Just think of me more like a friend.

319
00:24:34,181 --> 00:24:38,385
It's just that more and more
I've been having these...

320
00:24:38,408 --> 00:24:39,571
impulses.

321
00:24:44,136 --> 00:24:47,104
What kind of impulses?

322
00:24:52,494 --> 00:24:54,749
Strong ones.

323
00:25:13,596 --> 00:25:15,028
Here.

324
00:25:15,745 --> 00:25:18,492
The Lazar Office tell me
he's crazy to work with you.

325
00:25:18,516 --> 00:25:22,543
Tell Swifty Lazar he should not have
overexposed his client on television.

326
00:25:22,567 --> 00:25:25,164
Unlike some we could mention.

327
00:25:27,681 --> 00:25:30,867
- Anthony Perkins.
- Oh...

328
00:25:30,891 --> 00:25:34,106
Think of the duality
he could bring to the role of Norman.

329
00:25:34,124 --> 00:25:36,697
The rage lurking behind that
little boy grin.

330
00:25:36,722 --> 00:25:40,339
The winsome charm he uses
to keep from being found out.

331
00:25:40,362 --> 00:25:44,859
Why, Alma,
you're not suggesting Mr. Perkins is...?

332
00:25:44,883 --> 00:25:46,562
Hm.

333
00:25:47,936 --> 00:25:49,745
What?

334
00:25:55,583 --> 00:25:57,829
I like your office.

335
00:26:00,796 --> 00:26:05,680
I can't count how many times
I've seen Strangers on a Train.

336
00:26:05,704 --> 00:26:08,476
And Rope.

337
00:26:08,499 --> 00:26:11,256
Well, Norman Bates is
the logical extension

338
00:26:11,257 --> 00:26:14,012
of those two characters in that movie.

339
00:26:14,033 --> 00:26:17,873
Appealing, sensitive,
suffering the terrible burden

340
00:26:17,896 --> 00:26:21,430
of being forced to pretend to be
something he is not.

341
00:26:24,877 --> 00:26:29,362
I'm sick of all this romantic crap
the studios keep shoving me into.

342
00:26:29,374 --> 00:26:32,262
But my only worry is,

343
00:26:32,286 --> 00:26:35,589
well, playing Norman might
cut too close to home.

344
00:26:37,049 --> 00:26:39,070
How so?

345
00:26:41,689 --> 00:26:48,417
When I was younger,
I was incredibly close to my mother.

346
00:26:48,441 --> 00:26:52,759
So close that I remember
wishing my father would drop dead.

347
00:26:54,463 --> 00:26:58,669
And then when I was five,
he did just that.

348
00:26:58,693 --> 00:27:00,970
He keeled over from a heart attack.

349
00:27:07,813 --> 00:27:11,681
You see I've been guilty my whole life,
Mr. Hitchcock.

350
00:27:16,961 --> 00:27:19,775
You know,
I'm getting blisters just watching you.

351
00:27:19,799 --> 00:27:21,337
Oh, stop complaining.

352
00:27:21,360 --> 00:27:24,261
A bit of fresh air and exercise
will do you good.

353
00:27:24,284 --> 00:27:26,115
I'm going to have a drink.

354
00:27:26,116 --> 00:27:27,945
No you're not. You're
going to finish that hedge.

355
00:27:27,956 --> 00:27:29,312
You've got to go all the
way around there, all

356
00:27:29,313 --> 00:27:30,667
the way around there, all
the way around there.

357
00:27:30,691 --> 00:27:32,996
- It's impossible. I can't do that.
- Yes you can.

358
00:27:35,620 --> 00:27:40,274
You know, I was thinking, if I could
get Grace Kelly to play the girl,

359
00:27:40,298 --> 00:27:42,458
they'd let me get away with murder.

360
00:27:42,482 --> 00:27:46,433
Well you can't. She's a princess now,
which makes her permanently unattainable.

361
00:27:46,457 --> 00:27:48,758
And all the more desirable.

362
00:27:48,781 --> 00:27:52,283
What about Deborah Kerr?
Lew mentioned her.

363
00:27:52,306 --> 00:27:54,440
No, she's too Scottish.

364
00:27:56,025 --> 00:27:58,527
What about Janet Leigh?

365
00:27:58,551 --> 00:28:02,807
I know she's normally the "good girl,"
but she was awfully good in Touch of Evil.

366
00:28:02,831 --> 00:28:07,230
You remember how you always used to remark
on her figure at the Wassermans' parties?

367
00:28:08,646 --> 00:28:10,401
Yeah.

368
00:28:16,112 --> 00:28:18,188
- Good evening.
- Hello.

369
00:28:18,213 --> 00:28:20,105
- Lovely to see you.
- Charmed.

370
00:28:20,128 --> 00:28:22,124
- Hi.
- Hello, Janet. How are you?

371
00:28:22,148 --> 00:28:24,062
Wonderful to see you.

372
00:28:24,085 --> 00:28:27,918
- Well, my dear, you look very beautiful.
- Thank you.

373
00:28:27,942 --> 00:28:29,996
Very beautiful.

374
00:28:33,916 --> 00:28:36,108
Of course the real
secret of Mrs. Simpson's

375
00:28:36,109 --> 00:28:38,300
appeal to the Duke of Windsor

376
00:28:38,323 --> 00:28:42,132
was that she could make a toothpick
feel like a cigar.

377
00:28:43,717 --> 00:28:46,674
Oh, I've been so immersed
in preparing to play Marion

378
00:28:46,698 --> 00:28:49,121
I'd almost forgotten how to laugh.

379
00:28:49,144 --> 00:28:50,512
- Oh, really?
- Yes.

380
00:28:50,536 --> 00:28:53,889
Now, now, you must try
the banana shortcake.

381
00:28:53,903 --> 00:28:56,791
Oh, no. Nothing for me, thank you.
I'm watching my figure.

382
00:28:56,815 --> 00:28:59,755
Yes, you're not the only one.
We're fine, thank you.

383
00:28:59,779 --> 00:29:01,567
George, bring her the banana shortcake.

384
00:29:01,591 --> 00:29:04,984
In fact, make that two large portions.
Thank you.

385
00:29:05,008 --> 00:29:09,381
Now tell me, my dear, how else have you
prepared for the part of Marion Crane?

386
00:29:09,404 --> 00:29:11,859
Well, I've written an entire history
for her,

387
00:29:11,882 --> 00:29:15,457
which seems a little silly, I know,
but it really does help.

388
00:29:15,480 --> 00:29:18,099
- It doesn't sound silly at all.
- No?

389
00:29:18,116 --> 00:29:21,648
Why don't you tell us
one of her deepest secrets?

390
00:29:24,067 --> 00:29:27,360
Well, she leads a double life.

391
00:29:27,383 --> 00:29:30,824
At the Lowery Office,
she wears Tweed perfume.

392
00:29:30,847 --> 00:29:33,172
But when she's with Sam,

393
00:29:33,196 --> 00:29:37,775
she recklessly breaks out
her most expensive bottle.

394
00:29:37,799 --> 00:29:40,170
"My Sin" by Lanvin.

395
00:29:41,407 --> 00:29:42,874
- "My Sin"?
- Yes.

396
00:29:42,898 --> 00:29:44,861
Good Lord!

397
00:29:44,877 --> 00:29:47,643
I do have a concern or two.

398
00:29:47,667 --> 00:29:51,892
I'm an actress, of course,
but I'm first a wife and a mother.

399
00:29:51,916 --> 00:29:55,145
And I'm just curious to know...

400
00:29:55,168 --> 00:29:57,894
How are you going to shoot
this shower scene?

401
00:29:57,918 --> 00:30:00,642
Yes, you and the Shurlock Office.

402
00:30:00,665 --> 00:30:05,843
It's only that, well, from here up,
I'm not exactly boyish.

403
00:30:05,867 --> 00:30:09,079
Allow me to set your mind at rest,
my dear.

404
00:30:09,102 --> 00:30:12,578
I will be shooting short bits of film
from various angles.

405
00:30:12,601 --> 00:30:16,693
Cut together, the montage
will only suggest nudity.

406
00:30:16,716 --> 00:30:18,124
Suggest violence.

407
00:30:18,147 --> 00:30:20,533
Nothing will actually be shown.

408
00:30:21,646 --> 00:30:24,545
But of course, having you in the shower

409
00:30:24,557 --> 00:30:28,807
would make it all the more,
well, titillating.

410
00:30:30,568 --> 00:30:32,351
Will you excuse me?

411
00:30:47,937 --> 00:30:50,508
Alma, dear, how lovely to see you.

412
00:30:50,532 --> 00:30:52,986
Oh, hello, Lillian.

413
00:30:53,009 --> 00:30:54,829
You're looking a little pale.

414
00:30:54,853 --> 00:30:58,194
No wonder with that thing
your husband's working on now.

415
00:30:58,214 --> 00:31:00,426
You can't possibly approve.

416
00:31:00,450 --> 00:31:03,623
Why are you letting him do
something so tasteless?

417
00:31:03,647 --> 00:31:07,314
Don't upset yourself, darling.
It's only a bloody movie.

418
00:31:24,155 --> 00:31:28,159
I can't believe
you made Vera Miles play the sister.

419
00:31:28,171 --> 00:31:31,998
Well, I've still got her under contract.
May as well get something out of her.

420
00:31:32,021 --> 00:31:34,786
Rather a thankless role,
don't you think?

421
00:31:34,809 --> 00:31:37,660
For an utterly thankless girl.

422
00:31:50,538 --> 00:31:52,229
Horrible.

423
00:31:52,253 --> 00:31:54,977
The old man really is unhappy with me,
isn't he?

424
00:31:55,001 --> 00:31:57,779
Wait till you see the undergarments
he has picked out for you.

425
00:31:59,929 --> 00:32:04,091
Okay. Well, I am just going to
have to keep telling myself,

426
00:32:04,114 --> 00:32:07,854
one more picture
and I'm free as a bird.

427
00:32:21,679 --> 00:32:25,465
So I've made a list of places
where we can tighten our belts.

428
00:32:25,483 --> 00:32:27,256
Huh?

429
00:32:27,978 --> 00:32:31,460
We could all learn the art of
self-restraint, couldn't we, Alfred?

430
00:32:32,822 --> 00:32:36,970
Gardeners once a week,
weekend off for the driver...

431
00:32:36,994 --> 00:32:40,287
No, that's impossible.
We'll have to find other places to cut.

432
00:32:40,311 --> 00:32:42,131
There aren't any other places.

433
00:32:42,143 --> 00:32:46,333
And there's be no more shipments
flown in from Maxim's of Paris.

434
00:32:46,368 --> 00:32:48,700
We can't afford it.

435
00:32:48,723 --> 00:32:51,618
The foie gras at Chasen's
is more than adequate.

436
00:32:51,642 --> 00:32:55,653
But those geese are from Barstow,
not from Marseilles.

437
00:32:55,677 --> 00:32:58,278
Yes, well we all have
to make our sacrifices

438
00:32:58,279 --> 00:33:00,878
for the greater good, don't we, Alfred?

439
00:33:34,615 --> 00:33:36,989
I'll go get the knives.

440
00:33:59,885 --> 00:34:02,729
Am I making a terrible mistake?

441
00:34:05,979 --> 00:34:08,691
What if it's another Vertigo?

442
00:34:08,714 --> 00:34:12,234
Just get the first take under your belt.
You'll be fine.

443
00:34:22,210 --> 00:34:24,776
Are you decent, my dear?

444
00:34:26,064 --> 00:34:28,107
- Good morning.
- Good morning.

445
00:34:28,131 --> 00:34:30,766
Am I all right?

446
00:34:30,778 --> 00:34:33,807
- Perfect.
- Wow.

447
00:34:33,831 --> 00:34:35,439
- Morning.
- Morning.

448
00:34:35,463 --> 00:34:38,313
I want to thank you once again
for this opportunity, Mr. Hitchcock.

449
00:34:38,332 --> 00:34:40,412
You may call me "Hitch."
Hold the cock.

450
00:34:40,435 --> 00:34:43,699
Well look at you two.
America's favorite boy and girl next door.

451
00:34:43,723 --> 00:34:45,917
Yes, and we're about to move
to a whole new neighborhood.

452
00:34:45,940 --> 00:34:48,899
- Morning, Janet. Morning, Tony.
- Morning, Vera.

453
00:34:48,922 --> 00:34:51,482
- Thanks for the wardrobe, Hitch.
- Do you approve?

454
00:34:51,505 --> 00:34:53,343
You're the genius.

455
00:34:53,364 --> 00:34:56,194
One thing, though.
My script is missing its last ten pages.

456
00:34:56,217 --> 00:35:00,659
Everyone's script is missing ten pages
until Alma finishes the revisions.

457
00:35:00,682 --> 00:35:03,019
You're just in time for the Oath.

458
00:35:03,042 --> 00:35:06,571
- The what?
- The Oath.

459
00:35:06,595 --> 00:35:09,765
- Good morning, everyone.
- Good morning.

460
00:35:09,789 --> 00:35:13,029
Would you all raise your right hands?

461
00:35:13,053 --> 00:35:15,378
That includes you, Vera Miles.

462
00:35:18,138 --> 00:35:21,379
- I do solemnly promise...
- I do solemnly promise...

463
00:35:21,403 --> 00:35:24,955
- That I will not divulge...
- That I will not divulge...

464
00:35:24,979 --> 00:35:28,189
The plot nor the many
secrets of Psycho...

465
00:35:28,190 --> 00:35:31,399
The plot nor the many
secrets of Psycho...

466
00:35:31,422 --> 00:35:35,309
- To friends, relatives...
- To friends, relatives...

467
00:35:35,333 --> 00:35:37,771
- Trade reporters...
- Trade reporters...

468
00:35:37,795 --> 00:35:42,053
Not even outgoing
President Dwight D. Eisenhower.

469
00:35:42,076 --> 00:35:43,741
Thank you all very much.

470
00:37:30,246 --> 00:37:33,673
Here we are, Norman's inner sanctum.

471
00:37:39,226 --> 00:37:40,692
Now, Hitch.

472
00:37:40,716 --> 00:37:45,201
Explain to me
why I'm watching Marion undress?

473
00:37:45,224 --> 00:37:47,044
I feel like I should
take offense at that.

474
00:37:47,068 --> 00:37:50,005
Perhaps Norman
secretly watched his mother

475
00:37:50,029 --> 00:37:53,233
preparing for her nightly bath.

476
00:37:53,256 --> 00:37:56,168
Yes, maybe there was a transom
over the bathroom door?

477
00:37:56,191 --> 00:37:59,868
Yeah, which he could access
by climbing on a chair,

478
00:37:59,891 --> 00:38:03,120
so long as he was stealthy.

479
00:38:03,144 --> 00:38:06,748
A boy's first glimpse of a naked woman
